Use of APS bibliographic metadata
---------------------------------

The Digital Object Identifiers (DOIs) and article titles distributed under
`runs/`, in `benchmark/ground_truth.jsonl.gz`, and in
`embedding/umap_default_coordinates.csv.gz` are
bibliographic metadata for articles published in the journals of the
American Physical Society (APS). They are included here with the Society's
permission for the purpose of accompanying this paper.

The American Physical Society retains all rights to the underlying article
text. This release does NOT include abstracts, full text, references, or
any other portion of APS-copyrighted content. Only DOIs, titles,
classification predictions produced by the pipeline described in the paper,
existing APS PhySH labels for labeled articles, and derived UMAP coordinates
are distributed.

Any reuse must:
  - acknowledge the American Physical Society as the source of the
    bibliographic metadata (DOIs and titles) and PhySH labels, and
  - cite the accompanying paper for the classification predictions and
    method, per `CITATION.cff`.

PhySH classification scheme
---------------------------

The Physics Subject Headings (PhySH) classification scheme used here was
developed and is maintained by the American Physical Society. The taxonomy
mapping files distributed under `taxonomy/` reflect PhySH labels observed in
APS metadata through 2025.

APS metadata access
-------------------

This repository does not redistribute the full APS metadata corpus. APS
open-access metadata can be accessed through https://harvest.aps.org without
a key. Full access to the Harvest API typically requires a separate agreement
with APS, usually by IP address. To initiate that process, contact
customercare@aps.org.

